data.name: lblPrintoutExplanation.Text
data.value:
Use these Straddling Checkerboard blank templates to create your own encipherment system. Create your own key (and two numbers) and note them down, and use this to fill in the squares as instructed in the "ABOUT" page.
Remember, if there are any squares left over, leave them blank, as that will not affect your encoding.

data.name: lblCaesarCracking.Text
data.value:
Decryption, or "cracking", is the process of finding a way of obtaining the plaintext from ciphertext without knowing the key.
If we know that a piece of ciphertext was enciphered using the Caesar cipher, the simplest way to retrieve the original plaintext is to simply perform a brute-force attack. Since there are a limited number of possible shifts (26 in English), they can each be tested in turn. We can essentially perform the same Caesar cipher upon the ciphertext, and one of the 26 possible keys will return the plaintext.
A good example of this is the usage of the Caesar cipher with a key of 13 (specifically known as ROT13). Once we encipher plaintext with a key of 13, re-enciphering the ciphertext will result in the original plaintext!

data.name: lblStraddlingInfo1.Text
data.value:
The Straddling Checkerboard is not actually an entire cipher that was used, but rather, a component within the VIC Cipher. The VIC Cipher was arguably the most complex hand-operated cipher ever seen when it was first discovered.
The VIC Cipher consists of several important integrated components, including mod 10 chain addition, a lagged Fibonacci generator, a disrupted double transposition as well as a straddling checkerboard. Thus, the straddling checkerboard derives its significance as part of one of the most complex ciphers ever. The VIC Cipher actually remained unbroken for four years by the FBI, and it was only broken when its inventor, Reino Häyhänen, a Russian spy, defected. The beauty of such a cipher was that it involved not only a substitution and two transpositions, but also is passed through the Straddling Checkerboard to obtain the substituion, and then split in half. This was all made even more incredible by the fact that an agent enciphering a message only needed to remember four simple key words.
To make all of that simpler, the Straddling Checkerboard will be focused on, but it should be borne in mind that this was simply a small part in one of the most ingenious hand-encryption schemes ever!

data.name: lblStraddlingInfo2.Text
data.value:
A Straddling Checkerboard is simply a table that is used to convert plaintext into digits, achieving fractionation (a fancy way to obfuscate information).
It takes a key, and two digits. In the table below, the key is seen to be arranged as the first characters in the table, and the two digits are the cell columns that are skipped in the first row of letters. The two digits are also used to label the second and third row of letters. And once the table is generated, simply generate the number to replace each plaintext letter by the numbers labelling its row and column (respectively).

data.name: lblStraddlingInfo3.Text
data.value: The Checkerboard on the left doesn't use any special key at all, and so contains normal alphabetical letters in order. The right checkerboard however, has a key, and so the remaining alphabet follows the key. You can see a '#' and a '.' filling in the space on the right checkerboard as well. However, our implementation will not add 'filler' characters, as that is an alternate version.
